1
00:00:01,500 --> 00:00:02,439
Two weeks ago,

2
00:00:02,440 --> 00:00:05,419
an invisible dome crashed
down on Chester's mill,

3
00:00:05,420 --> 00:00:07,379
cutting us off from the rest of the world.

4
00:00:07,380 --> 00:00:10,189
Why the dome is here or
what mysteries lie ahead,

5
00:00:10,190 --> 00:00:11,349
we still don't know.

6
00:00:11,350 --> 00:00:13,759
Every day it tests our limits,

7
00:00:13,760 --> 00:00:16,910
bringing out the best and the worst in us.

8
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:20,620
Some say we'll be stuck here forever,

9
00:00:20,980 --> 00:00:24,660
but we will never stop
fighting to find a way out.

10
00:00:28,920 --> 00:00:30,280
Angie's dead.

11
00:00:30,620 --> 00:00:31,629
Oh, my lord.

12
00:00:31,630 --> 00:00:33,380
Is this where you point the finger at me?

13
00:00:33,390 --> 00:00:34,969
Neither of us would
do something like this.

14
00:00:34,970 --> 00:00:35,989
So, then, who would?

15
00:00:35,990 --> 00:00:38,939
Is it possible to love someone
so much that you'd hurt them?

16
00:00:38,940 --> 00:00:40,599
But you'd never do anything violent

17
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:42,529
to the person you loved, would you?

18
00:00:42,530 --> 00:00:44,499
First we lose Linda, now Angie.

19
00:00:44,500 --> 00:00:46,399
I thought the dome was
supposed to protect us.

20
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:48,859
No, it's up to us...
To protect each other.

21
00:00:48,860 --> 00:00:50,599
There are too many people in here

22
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:52,470
for our limited resources.

23
00:00:52,480 --> 00:00:53,840
We can't all survive.

24
00:00:53,900 --> 00:00:54,639
Who is she?

25
00:00:54,640 --> 00:00:55,599
Hey, what's your name?

26
00:00:55,600 --> 00:00:57,249
It was the girl we saw in the woods.

27
00:00:57,250 --> 00:00:59,040
They found a bloody
shoeprint at the school.

28
00:00:59,050 --> 00:01:00,289
This looks like her.

29
00:01:00,290 --> 00:01:01,429
Pauline drew this?

30
00:01:01,430 --> 00:01:02,620
20 years ago.

31
00:01:12,610 --> 00:01:13,650
I was just...

32
00:01:16,020 --> 00:01:16,920
Looking.

33
00:01:17,170 --> 00:01:18,160
For what?

34
00:01:19,230 --> 00:01:20,590
Reminders.

35
00:01:21,490 --> 00:01:24,360
I feel like I know you from somewhere.

36
00:01:24,530 --> 00:01:26,800
Your license says you're from zenith.

37
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:29,000
You're not from here?

38
00:01:30,540 --> 00:01:31,910
Where are you from?

39
00:01:32,110 --> 00:01:33,120
I don't know.

40
00:01:33,490 --> 00:01:35,150
You interrogating her?

41
00:01:36,400 --> 00:01:37,580
No, I'm...

42
00:01:40,890 --> 00:01:42,929
I'm just trying to figure
out who she is, okay?

43
00:01:42,930 --> 00:01:44,570
We don't even know her name.

44
00:01:45,820 --> 00:01:47,489
Try to patient with her.

45
00:01:47,490 --> 00:01:50,989
I'm sorry, I'm not buying this
whole little baby bird act.

46
00:01:50,990 --> 00:01:52,839
- It's not an act.
- Are you sure about that?

47
00:01:52,840 --> 00:01:53,799
'Cause I just came in here

48
00:01:53,800 --> 00:01:55,700
and found her going through my stuff.

49
00:01:57,903 --> 00:02:00,350
I... I just want you to be more careful

50
00:02:00,360 --> 00:02:02,780
about bringing strays into our house.

51
00:02:03,270 --> 00:02:04,799
Well, let's not forget the last stray

52
00:02:04,800 --> 00:02:06,500
that I brought in was you.

53
00:02:10,490 --> 00:02:12,129
Gonna head down to the diner.

54
00:02:12,130 --> 00:02:15,140
Jim's mandatory citizen registration?

55
00:02:25,380 --> 00:02:26,810
Can I come with you?

56
00:02:27,370 --> 00:02:28,560
Of course you can.

57
00:02:29,770 --> 00:02:32,360
Do you think someone will recognize me?

58
00:02:35,220 --> 00:02:36,790
We'll figure it out, sweetie.

59
00:02:47,510 --> 00:02:48,730
What's that scent?

60
00:02:49,150 --> 00:02:50,870
It's a dram of cassia oil.

61
00:02:51,240 --> 00:02:52,820
- It's nice, huh?
- Yeah.

62
00:02:52,830 --> 00:02:55,349
Could you make a cologne?

63
00:02:55,350 --> 00:02:57,190
For you? Yeah.

64
00:02:57,330 --> 00:02:58,699
What do you have, a big date?

65
00:02:58,700 --> 00:03:00,249
It's been nine years since, uh...

66
00:03:00,250 --> 00:03:02,340
- Pauline passed.
- Yeah.

67
00:03:02,380 --> 00:03:04,350
Yeah, I still think about her every day.

68
00:03:06,730 --> 00:03:08,310
Want you to know I was, uh,

69
00:03:08,520 --> 00:03:11,890
grateful for your
support during that time.

70
00:03:11,900 --> 00:03:13,109
It couldn't have been easy,

71
00:03:13,110 --> 00:03:15,020
given your history with her.

72
00:03:16,500 --> 00:03:18,420
The better man won that battle, Jim.

73
00:03:19,030 --> 00:03:20,580
Who's this lucky lady?

74
00:03:21,610 --> 00:03:22,619
Rebecca pine.

75
00:03:22,620 --> 00:03:26,289
She's a science teacher
at the high school.

76
00:03:26,290 --> 00:03:27,690
Been working together.

77
00:03:27,760 --> 00:03:31,020
I'll just say there's, uh,
something interesting about her.

78
00:03:32,950 --> 00:03:33,760
If you want,

79
00:03:33,770 --> 00:03:36,289
I could whip up a fragrance for you, Jim,

80
00:03:36,290 --> 00:03:38,150
that'd get your pheromones kicking.

81
00:03:38,240 --> 00:03:39,830
Appreciate that, Lyle.

82
00:03:42,610 --> 00:03:45,030
None of that, uh, cassia oil, though.

83
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:48,190
Comes off a bit effeminate.

84
00:03:49,970 --> 00:03:51,430
What are you smiling about?

85
00:03:52,120 --> 00:03:54,280
I don't know. Just
something about the day.

86
00:03:55,880 --> 00:03:57,480
Seems auspicious.

87
00:03:57,520 --> 00:03:59,169
Expect you later at the sweetbriar

88
00:03:59,170 --> 00:04:00,430
for the registration?

89
00:04:00,720 --> 00:04:01,600
Yeah.

90
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:03,870
Yeah, see you down there.

91
00:04:04,990 --> 00:04:07,560
Answer every question to
the best of your knowledge.

92
00:04:08,300 --> 00:04:10,600
This survey will provide us
with the proper information

93
00:04:10,610 --> 00:04:12,810
to get everyone the resources they need.

94
00:04:19,150 --> 00:04:20,730
Should I look around?

95
00:04:20,870 --> 00:04:22,810
Yes. Uh, I'll be right here.

96
00:04:27,240 --> 00:04:29,369
Has that girl remembered
anything about Angie yet?

97
00:04:29,370 --> 00:04:32,249
Don't worry. We're gonna find
the person who killed her.

98
00:04:32,250 --> 00:04:33,130
Also,

99
00:04:33,220 --> 00:04:35,270
there were four hands a couple days ago.

100
00:04:35,280 --> 00:04:37,269
Now, with my sister
gone, there's only three.

101
00:04:37,270 --> 00:04:39,090
Would the dome let her die?

102
00:04:39,640 --> 00:04:40,900
What if we were wrong?

103
00:04:41,380 --> 00:04:43,279
And the dome isn't here to protect us?

104
00:04:43,280 --> 00:04:44,310
I don't know.

105
00:04:44,610 --> 00:04:46,990
If you don't know, who will?

106
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:50,290
I've got... I noticed you
didn't have one of these.

107
00:04:50,370 --> 00:04:52,610
- Thank you.
- I'm just helping out.

108
00:04:53,330 --> 00:04:54,120
Joe?

109
00:04:55,170 --> 00:04:56,789
I need a favor.

110
00:04:56,790 --> 00:04:58,619
Can you open up the
project room at the school

111
00:04:58,620 --> 00:04:59,749
and make sure it's prepped?

112
00:04:59,750 --> 00:05:02,669
Remember that windmill project
we did on alternative energy?

113
00:05:02,670 --> 00:05:04,739
- Yeah, I still have the specs on my tablet.
- Great.

114
00:05:04,740 --> 00:05:07,139
Bring it. We're gonna be
replicating the concept

115
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:08,609
on a much larger scale

116
00:05:08,610 --> 00:05:11,029
to generate electricity for the town.

117
00:05:11,030 --> 00:05:11,950
Cool.

118
00:05:12,480 --> 00:05:13,929
You can take your friend.

119
00:05:13,930 --> 00:05:15,780
I don't go to school here.

120
00:05:15,960 --> 00:05:19,759
Well, everyone between 14 and
18 is expected to participate.

121
00:05:19,760 --> 00:05:23,370
And there goes the last
perk of dome living.

122
00:05:23,480 --> 00:05:24,930
Do you recognize anyone?

123
00:05:25,600 --> 00:05:27,059
You can help out, too.

124
00:05:27,060 --> 00:05:29,050
No, uh, she stays with me.

125
00:05:29,840 --> 00:05:31,070
Help with what?

126
00:05:31,180 --> 00:05:32,270
An experiment.

127
00:05:33,120 --> 00:05:34,070
It's okay.

128
00:05:34,440 --> 00:05:36,080
I like to help.

129
00:05:42,250 --> 00:05:43,230
Look out for her.

130
00:05:45,260 --> 00:05:48,660
So you're really embracing your
new responsibilities, aren't you?

131
00:05:48,670 --> 00:05:52,570
Well, I serve at the
pleasure of our councilmen.

132
00:05:52,800 --> 00:05:54,100
Please fill that out.

133
00:06:01,140 --> 00:06:04,090
Why torture yourself if you don't know?

134
00:06:04,970 --> 00:06:07,510
Angie's bracelet was under my cot.

135
00:06:09,410 --> 00:06:10,740
You loved her, right?

136
00:06:12,270 --> 00:06:13,650
More than anything.

137
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:15,819
Do you really think

138
00:06:15,820 --> 00:06:18,370
you could have killed the person you loved

139
00:06:18,450 --> 00:06:19,640
more than anything?

140
00:06:20,270 --> 00:06:21,020
No.

141
00:06:21,680 --> 00:06:22,890
I... I don't know.

142
00:06:23,940 --> 00:06:26,100
Why can't... why can't I remember?

143
00:06:33,590 --> 00:06:36,070
The night Angie was killed,
you said you blacked out.

144
00:06:36,390 --> 00:06:38,010
Those were the words you used.

145
00:06:39,240 --> 00:06:42,210
I don't know what this means. It
might not mean anything. But...

146
00:06:43,130 --> 00:06:44,340
Your mom...

147
00:06:44,380 --> 00:06:46,200
She had blackouts, too.

148
00:06:46,320 --> 00:06:48,659
Fugue states, the doctor called them.

149
00:06:48,660 --> 00:06:51,259
"Disassociative" or...
Something like that.

150
00:06:51,260 --> 00:06:52,099
Well, what would happen to

151
00:06:52,100 --> 00:06:53,829
her when she had them?
Would she get violent?

152
00:06:53,830 --> 00:06:55,939
What's important is
that, sometimes, afterward

153
00:06:55,940 --> 00:06:58,239
she would go back to where
she was when the blackout hit

154
00:06:58,240 --> 00:07:00,280
and she would get these flashes.

155
00:07:00,290 --> 00:07:03,030
Glimpses, little bits
of memory coming back.

156
00:07:04,060 --> 00:07:06,930
So I should go back
to where I found Angie.

157
00:07:07,630 --> 00:07:09,090
Maybe something'll come back.

158
00:07:09,970 --> 00:07:10,900
Hey, James.

159
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:13,530
No matter what, you and me are family.

160
00:07:14,650 --> 00:07:15,880
We'll figure this out.

161
00:07:28,910 --> 00:07:32,019
All right, folks, grab any receptacle
you can find, folks. Let's go.

162
00:07:32,020 --> 00:07:33,609
Precipitation's scarce;

163
00:07:33,610 --> 00:07:36,640
let's collect as much
drinkable water as we can.

164
00:07:37,310 --> 00:07:39,320
She's a little bossy, don't you think?

165
00:07:40,540 --> 00:07:41,410
Wait.

166
00:07:50,540 --> 00:07:52,269
It's raining blood.

167
00:07:59,690 --> 00:08:06,263
Under the dome
stagione 02b- episodio 03
�force majeure�

168
00:08:06,293 --> 00:08:13,164
<i>Angels & Demons - international subs
[Www.Facebook.Com/ad.Italiansubtitles]</i>

169
00:08:16,200 --> 00:08:17,760
It can't be blood, can it?

170
00:08:18,290 --> 00:08:20,300
I don't think it's cherry kool-aid.

171
00:08:22,040 --> 00:08:23,599
Ah! It burns.

172
00:08:23,600 --> 00:08:25,320
Let's go wash it off. Come on.

173
00:08:27,780 --> 00:08:30,900
All right, listen up, everybody.
Stay calm and stay inside.

174
00:08:31,480 --> 00:08:34,140
We don't leave the cafe till
the rain stops, all right?

175
00:08:35,150 --> 00:08:35,949
- Jim.
- Yeah?

176
00:08:35,950 --> 00:08:37,870
You know what this is about, don't you?

177
00:08:39,110 --> 00:08:40,350
The ten plagues.

178
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:43,989
Lyle, don't start getting
all biblical on me now, okay?

179
00:08:43,990 --> 00:08:45,439
Oh, but that swarm the other day.

180
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:47,209
That may as well have been locusts.

181
00:08:47,210 --> 00:08:49,499
Butterflies are not locusts, Lyle.

182
00:08:49,500 --> 00:08:51,809
Jim, it's like three
plagues rolled into one.

183
00:08:51,810 --> 00:08:54,219
Storm of fire, boils,

184
00:08:54,220 --> 00:08:55,879
and water turns to blood.

185
00:08:55,880 --> 00:08:57,070
It's not blood.

186
00:08:57,360 --> 00:08:58,520
How do you know?

187
00:08:58,550 --> 00:08:59,989
Well, blood doesn't burn.

188
00:08:59,990 --> 00:09:01,859
Yeah, but it doesn't usually
fall out of the sky like that,

189
00:09:01,860 --> 00:09:02,829
either, but take a look.

190
00:09:02,830 --> 00:09:05,589
There was a red rain phenomenon
in India a decade ago.

191
00:09:05,590 --> 00:09:08,830
It was caused by spores
from an abnormal algae bloom.

192
00:09:09,300 --> 00:09:11,359
I'm looking at scripture
to tell me what this is.

193
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:12,640
What are you looking at?

194
00:09:13,350 --> 00:09:15,469
Science. Like...

195
00:09:15,470 --> 00:09:19,090
When the dome magnetized
or the crops were infested.

196
00:09:19,380 --> 00:09:22,799
So you'll solve everything,
huh? You and science?

197
00:09:22,800 --> 00:09:25,149
Or go down trying. Okay, um,

198
00:09:25,150 --> 00:09:26,380
I collected a sample.

199
00:09:26,450 --> 00:09:28,020
I can analyze it at the school lab

200
00:09:28,070 --> 00:09:30,119
and look for a way to
neutralize the acidity.

201
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:31,459
- Little help.
- Sam.

202
00:09:31,460 --> 00:09:33,029
Put her down over there.
I'm glad you're here.

203
00:09:33,030 --> 00:09:35,359
We've got a few more people who
might need medical attention.

204
00:09:35,360 --> 00:09:36,820
- Burning skin?
- Yeah.

205
00:09:37,050 --> 00:09:38,649
Everybody's stable... excuse me.

206
00:09:38,650 --> 00:09:39,850
We should go back out.

207
00:09:40,300 --> 00:09:42,099
I saw other people stranded out there.

208
00:09:42,100 --> 00:09:44,879
There's a... there's an ambulance
and med center. That's close by.

209
00:09:44,880 --> 00:09:46,190
Cover her up, let's go.

210
00:09:49,020 --> 00:09:49,860
What is it?

211
00:09:50,360 --> 00:09:51,130
It's just...

212
00:09:57,060 --> 00:09:58,180
What are you doing here?

213
00:09:58,220 --> 00:09:59,940
- Homework.
- What about you?

214
00:10:00,860 --> 00:10:01,750
Same.

215
00:10:02,990 --> 00:10:04,190
Anyways,

216
00:10:04,220 --> 00:10:05,260
I'm gonna take off now.

217
00:10:05,350 --> 00:10:06,430
You can't.

218
00:10:06,670 --> 00:10:07,590
Why not?

219
00:10:08,980 --> 00:10:11,160
You haven't been outside
for a while, have you?

220
00:10:18,190 --> 00:10:19,350
Apocalypse.

221
00:10:20,450 --> 00:10:21,330
What'd you say?

222
00:10:21,530 --> 00:10:23,770
The apocalypse... what
Lyle was talking about.

223
00:10:24,280 --> 00:10:25,210
Do you believe in it?

224
00:10:25,980 --> 00:10:29,189
I believe in the original
definition of "apocalypse."

225
00:10:29,190 --> 00:10:30,020
It's Greek.

226
00:10:30,030 --> 00:10:33,340
To uncover, or reveal.

227
00:10:33,610 --> 00:10:35,120
That's what crises do.

228
00:10:35,630 --> 00:10:39,140
They reveal character, strength.

229
00:10:42,190 --> 00:10:43,160
Or not.

230
00:10:44,970 --> 00:10:46,470
Think we're being tested?

231
00:10:47,480 --> 00:10:50,780
I mean, the rain, the
infestation, everything?

232
00:10:52,050 --> 00:10:55,080
Think it's a test from the dome

233
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:57,329
to see whether I'm worthy?

234
00:10:57,330 --> 00:10:59,420
Jim, we can solve this.

235
00:10:59,640 --> 00:11:01,499
The red algae must
have come from the lake,

236
00:11:01,500 --> 00:11:02,719
which could have gotten toxified

237
00:11:02,720 --> 00:11:04,109
from everything we've been dumping in it,

238
00:11:04,110 --> 00:11:06,459
not to mention, um, pesticides,

239
00:11:06,460 --> 00:11:09,100
trash fires, trapped exhaust from cars.

240
00:11:09,400 --> 00:11:11,330
Town's an environmental horror show.

241
00:11:11,810 --> 00:11:13,480
We're stuck inside, huh?

242
00:11:14,720 --> 00:11:17,220
Believe in me, and I will believe in you.

243
00:11:19,590 --> 00:11:21,570
Science and faith, huh?

244
00:11:23,970 --> 00:11:24,920
Look out!

245
00:11:50,900 --> 00:11:52,470
Is he okay?

246
00:11:54,690 --> 00:11:56,330
I don't think he's ever been okay.

247
00:11:59,290 --> 00:12:00,590
Are you okay?

248
00:12:01,160 --> 00:12:03,410
Yeah. Yeah, I'm fine.

249
00:12:06,280 --> 00:12:07,450
Will you give me a hand?

250
00:12:07,990 --> 00:12:09,360
I didn't hear a bell.

251
00:12:09,560 --> 00:12:10,250
Come on, nore.

252
00:12:10,260 --> 00:12:11,929
There's an extra tablet on the shelf.

253
00:12:11,930 --> 00:12:13,960
We got to look up the
specs on the windmill.

254
00:12:29,310 --> 00:12:30,900
Oh, my God.

255
00:12:32,220 --> 00:12:33,180
What is it?

256
00:12:34,130 --> 00:12:35,080
E-mail.

257
00:12:37,590 --> 00:12:38,890
I'm getting e-mail.

258
00:12:42,550 --> 00:12:43,710
This is big Jim.

259
00:12:44,070 --> 00:12:47,330
On motton road across from the killians.

260
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:48,930
Send help.

261
00:12:54,060 --> 00:12:55,380
Look at this.

262
00:12:55,430 --> 00:12:58,500
We're super trendy in Twitter land.

263
00:12:59,290 --> 00:13:01,050
Who's hounds of Diana?

264
00:13:01,230 --> 00:13:02,910
They're all over my page.

265
00:13:04,150 --> 00:13:05,550
Are they messages?

266
00:13:05,790 --> 00:13:08,700
Yeah. First since the dome came down.

267
00:13:09,240 --> 00:13:11,550
I don't know how the signal's
getting through, though.

268
00:13:15,450 --> 00:13:16,650
It's from my dad.

269
00:13:17,440 --> 00:13:18,760
What does it say?

270
00:13:21,270 --> 00:13:22,459
"Your mother and I pray every day

271
00:13:22,460 --> 00:13:24,250
"that we'll get to see you soon.

272
00:13:24,490 --> 00:13:26,920
"In the meantime, stay safe and be smart.

273
00:13:27,310 --> 00:13:29,100
You are the man of the house now."

274
00:13:31,850 --> 00:13:33,490
"Take care of your sister."

275
00:13:37,830 --> 00:13:39,080
What do I even say?

276
00:13:42,640 --> 00:13:44,900
Do I even tell them that Angie's dead?

277
00:13:46,840 --> 00:13:48,940
What if we never even get out of here?

278
00:13:51,890 --> 00:13:54,650
I mean, wouldn't it be better
if they just didn't know?

279
00:13:55,540 --> 00:13:58,090
If they're never gonna
see her again anyway?

280
00:14:01,622 --> 00:14:03,450
We'll figure it out, sweetie.

281
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:11,600
Feel like checking your messages?

282
00:14:12,250 --> 00:14:13,979
There's only so much fake-ass fan mail

283
00:14:13,980 --> 00:14:15,289
from wannabe dome groupies

284
00:14:15,290 --> 00:14:16,899
that I can read before I barf

285
00:14:16,900 --> 00:14:18,740
all over this wonderful
piece of machinery.

286
00:14:18,960 --> 00:14:20,960
- No, thanks.
- We're stuck in here.

287
00:14:21,660 --> 00:14:24,100
What else are you gonna
do, build windmills?

288
00:14:34,540 --> 00:14:35,860
"I can help you, James."

289
00:14:57,330 --> 00:15:00,320
Jim, respond if you're hearing this.

290
00:15:02,040 --> 00:15:03,340
That's the killians' farm.

291
00:15:03,380 --> 00:15:04,960
- Here?
- There.

292
00:15:05,020 --> 00:15:06,000
There he is.

293
00:15:08,380 --> 00:15:09,959
Julia, wait here.

294
00:15:09,960 --> 00:15:10,990
Get the kit ready.

295
00:15:20,250 --> 00:15:22,969
Jim? He's barely breathing.
Let's get him up. Come on.

296
00:15:22,970 --> 00:15:24,850
It could be anaphylactic shock.

297
00:15:45,930 --> 00:15:47,110
Guess you woke up.

298
00:15:51,060 --> 00:15:52,000
Where's big Jim?

299
00:15:52,930 --> 00:15:54,360
I guess where I left him.

300
00:15:56,110 --> 00:15:57,700
What did you do to him?

301
00:15:58,870 --> 00:16:00,050
You know, he's gonna be tickled

302
00:16:00,060 --> 00:16:01,990
you're this concerned
with his well-being.

303
00:16:02,040 --> 00:16:04,340
What did you do?

304
00:16:04,640 --> 00:16:05,920
I didn't do anything.

305
00:16:06,270 --> 00:16:08,810
If he's righteous, the rain'll spare him.

306
00:16:11,820 --> 00:16:14,770
Thing is, I've known
that guy my whole life.

307
00:16:15,320 --> 00:16:16,640
And righteousness?

308
00:16:20,750 --> 00:16:24,060
That's not something that ranks
high on his list of attributes.

309
00:16:26,220 --> 00:16:29,200
Self-righteousness, now, yeah.

310
00:16:29,210 --> 00:16:31,389
He's got that in spades.

311
00:16:31,390 --> 00:16:32,460
Listen!

312
00:16:33,600 --> 00:16:35,530
You have to let me out.

313
00:16:36,740 --> 00:16:39,569
This rain... I know how to stop it,

314
00:16:39,570 --> 00:16:41,069
and nobody else will get hurt.

315
00:16:41,070 --> 00:16:42,420
If you untie me,

316
00:16:42,630 --> 00:16:44,550
it'll be like you're
helping me to stop it.

317
00:16:46,430 --> 00:16:47,470
So help me.

318
00:16:48,890 --> 00:16:50,520
Help me stop it, Lyle.

319
00:16:50,880 --> 00:16:53,650
Yeah, I... I don't want to stop the rain.

320
00:16:54,980 --> 00:16:56,660
And neither does the dome.

321
00:16:57,520 --> 00:16:58,420
The dome?

322
00:17:00,130 --> 00:17:02,439
The dome does not want.

323
00:17:02,440 --> 00:17:05,890
You know why yahweh visited
the plagues on the Egyptians?

324
00:17:06,620 --> 00:17:11,010
To demonstrate his awesome,
terrible power to nonbelievers.

325
00:17:12,050 --> 00:17:14,440
They were swallowed up by the red sea.

326
00:17:16,070 --> 00:17:17,010
Yeah.

327
00:17:19,530 --> 00:17:21,040
This isn't yahweh.

328
00:17:23,330 --> 00:17:25,270
There's a new God in Chester's mill.

329
00:17:25,760 --> 00:17:28,020
It surrounds and embraces us all.

330
00:17:29,780 --> 00:17:32,290
And it's gonna show no mercy to infidels.

331
00:17:33,730 --> 00:17:35,500
You got a choice, Rebecca.

332
00:17:37,780 --> 00:17:39,580
I just pray you make the right one.

333
00:17:52,790 --> 00:17:53,589
What happened to him?

334
00:17:53,590 --> 00:17:55,970
He must have ingested too much
of whatever's in that rain.

335
00:17:56,920 --> 00:17:57,890
Hand me that pack.

336
00:17:58,000 --> 00:17:59,489
Hold on. Once you put that in,

337
00:17:59,490 --> 00:18:00,389
he won't be able to talk.

338
00:18:00,390 --> 00:18:02,470
Hey, Jim, what happened to Rebecca?

339
00:18:03,640 --> 00:18:04,590
Lyle.

340
00:18:06,100 --> 00:18:07,270
It was Lyle.

341
00:18:19,390 --> 00:18:20,420
What's that for?

342
00:18:21,290 --> 00:18:22,520
I don't want to hurt you,

343
00:18:23,850 --> 00:18:26,070
but I can't have you
interfering with the plan.

344
00:18:26,600 --> 00:18:28,490
What plan?

345
00:18:28,830 --> 00:18:30,110
End of days.

346
00:18:31,790 --> 00:18:33,240
After this rain stops,

347
00:18:34,270 --> 00:18:35,590
the rapture comes.

348
00:18:36,160 --> 00:18:38,710
True believers are gonna be
reunited in the hereafter.

349
00:18:41,220 --> 00:18:42,629
If you stop interfering with the plan,

350
00:18:42,630 --> 00:18:43,780
I won't have to hurt you.

351
00:18:45,140 --> 00:18:46,520
I'll never stop.

352
00:18:47,860 --> 00:18:49,380
I'm sorry to hear that, Rebecca.

353
00:18:50,750 --> 00:18:54,930
I indeed baptize you with
water unto repentance,

354
00:18:55,430 --> 00:18:58,490
but he that cometh
after is mightier than I.

355
00:18:59,050 --> 00:19:01,730
He shall baptize you with the holy ghost,

356
00:19:04,420 --> 00:19:05,520
and with fire.

357
00:19:22,050 --> 00:19:23,120
James,

358
00:19:23,690 --> 00:19:24,840
my love,

359
00:19:26,530 --> 00:19:27,750
my sweet son,

360
00:19:28,550 --> 00:19:30,390
by this time now,

361
00:19:31,200 --> 00:19:32,380
I expect you know,

362
00:19:32,790 --> 00:19:34,880
or have at least suspected the truth...

363
00:19:35,570 --> 00:19:36,660
That I'm alive.

364
00:19:38,170 --> 00:19:42,760
I hope, I pray that you get this message.

365
00:19:44,640 --> 00:19:47,640
You must have so many questions.

366
00:19:48,590 --> 00:19:51,500
And I know, in my heart,
that I will see you again.

367
00:19:52,720 --> 00:19:54,040
But in the meantime,

368
00:19:54,680 --> 00:19:56,190
if you need answers,

369
00:19:56,500 --> 00:19:58,810
talk to Lyle chumley.

370
00:20:00,120 --> 00:20:01,200
James.

371
00:20:02,360 --> 00:20:03,690
This is important.

372
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:06,180
Please listen.

373
00:20:07,500 --> 00:20:08,560
Talk to Lyle.

374
00:20:09,520 --> 00:20:11,540
Only to Lyle.

375
00:20:13,050 --> 00:20:14,050
And if my...

376
00:20:18,190 --> 00:20:19,610
No, no, no. No, no, no.
Come on, come on, come on.

377
00:20:19,850 --> 00:20:22,940
- Joe, Joe... what happened?
- That's so strange.

378
00:20:22,950 --> 00:20:24,490
Mine just did the same thing.

379
00:20:24,990 --> 00:20:26,430
We can't get access anywhere now.

380
00:20:26,730 --> 00:20:28,799
My tablet's working and the
signal's still coming through,

381
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:31,670
but there seems to be
some kind of... block.

382
00:20:32,960 --> 00:20:33,829
What are you doing?

383
00:20:33,830 --> 00:20:35,110
I got to go find someone.

384
00:20:35,670 --> 00:20:36,590
Junior.

385
00:20:38,480 --> 00:20:39,850
No, you can't go outside.

386
00:20:40,050 --> 00:20:41,090
It's dangerous.

387
00:20:43,170 --> 00:20:44,960
I always thought Lyle was harmless.

388
00:20:46,510 --> 00:20:47,619
Well, given the right circumstances,

389
00:20:47,620 --> 00:20:49,310
anybody's capable of anything.

390
00:20:50,160 --> 00:20:51,090
You really believe that?

391
00:20:51,260 --> 00:20:52,969
I believe that when things fall apart,

392
00:20:52,970 --> 00:20:54,560
people show their true colors.

393
00:20:55,060 --> 00:20:56,780
So, what, everyone's bad in the end?

394
00:20:57,090 --> 00:20:58,199
Well, this is just the perfect time

395
00:20:58,200 --> 00:21:00,120
to be having a debate
over the nature of man.

396
00:21:01,450 --> 00:21:02,820
These past few weeks,

397
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:06,680
haven't you also seen people
acting selflessly? Bravely?

398
00:21:06,690 --> 00:21:08,200
That's the exception to the rule.

399
00:21:08,570 --> 00:21:09,869
If this town's gonna survive,

400
00:21:09,870 --> 00:21:12,480
it's gonna need a firm hand
to keep everybody in check.

401
00:21:14,060 --> 00:21:15,360
Like big Jim's?

402
00:21:18,920 --> 00:21:19,960
Julia, look at this.

403
00:21:24,500 --> 00:21:25,940
"Summer '88."

404
00:21:25,970 --> 00:21:29,200
"Lyle, Sam and pauline."

405
00:21:40,260 --> 00:21:41,580
Sam? Sam, are you there?

406
00:21:42,700 --> 00:21:43,820
I'm here, Julia.

407
00:21:44,060 --> 00:21:46,590
We're at Lyle's shop.
He's not here, but we, uh,

408
00:21:46,890 --> 00:21:50,140
- we found something. A photograph.
- Of what?

409
00:21:50,270 --> 00:21:53,880
You, Lyle and pauline in 1988.

410
00:21:54,460 --> 00:21:55,800
They're holding hands.

411
00:21:56,100 --> 00:21:57,919
Yeah, that's right around the time

412
00:21:57,920 --> 00:21:59,260
he was seeing my sister.

413
00:22:00,050 --> 00:22:01,260
You never mentioned that.

414
00:22:01,470 --> 00:22:02,869
It was 25 years ago, Julia,

415
00:22:02,870 --> 00:22:04,480
I didn't even think about it until now.

416
00:22:04,750 --> 00:22:07,080
And I haven't spoken
to Lyle since she died.

417
00:22:09,740 --> 00:22:11,930
Well, do you have any
idea where he might be?

418
00:22:12,130 --> 00:22:14,700
Wish I did. If you find him, let me know.

419
00:22:14,910 --> 00:22:16,290
I got people to tend to here.

420
00:22:21,460 --> 00:22:22,340
What are you doing here?

421
00:22:23,030 --> 00:22:24,490
Heard you over the police radio.

422
00:22:25,670 --> 00:22:26,610
Thought I'd help out.

423
00:22:26,930 --> 00:22:29,040
Great. Here, look at this.

424
00:22:29,450 --> 00:22:30,940
Any idea where this was taken?

425
00:22:31,050 --> 00:22:33,070
This is my mom before she met my dad.

426
00:22:33,770 --> 00:22:35,390
Uh, it's by the cement factory.

427
00:22:35,420 --> 00:22:37,180
I used to build forts
there when I was a kid.

428
00:22:37,730 --> 00:22:38,929
Yeah, well, let's give it a shot.

429
00:22:38,930 --> 00:22:40,180
See if Lyle took her there.

430
00:22:41,490 --> 00:22:43,179
- So there's still a block?
- Yeah.

431
00:22:43,180 --> 00:22:45,900
We can't get access, but the
signal's still coming through.

432
00:22:46,280 --> 00:22:47,839
Maybe that means there must be a...

433
00:22:47,840 --> 00:22:50,720
- I don't know, a... a crack.
- In the dome?

434
00:22:51,190 --> 00:22:53,839
Joe, they fired their
biggest, baddest bomb at it

435
00:22:53,840 --> 00:22:55,449
and it didn't even make a dent.

436
00:22:55,450 --> 00:22:56,840
I don't mean, like, literally.

437
00:22:58,350 --> 00:23:00,499
What if the magnetism
caused some sort of...

438
00:23:00,500 --> 00:23:01,730
I don't know... wormhole?

439
00:23:02,280 --> 00:23:03,479
Now, all I'm saying is,

440
00:23:03,480 --> 00:23:05,950
if we found the source of the
signal we might find a way out.

441
00:23:07,590 --> 00:23:08,630
Want to go look?

442
00:23:11,490 --> 00:23:12,290
All right. Come on.

443
00:23:23,170 --> 00:23:24,070
Why?

444
00:23:25,440 --> 00:23:26,460
Why'd I save you?

445
00:23:27,560 --> 00:23:29,120
I may not be on your team...

446
00:23:29,460 --> 00:23:31,480
Hell, I may even
hate your damn guts...

447
00:23:32,290 --> 00:23:34,160
But that doesn't mean
I'm gonna let you die.

448
00:23:41,020 --> 00:23:42,360
At least, not yet.

449
00:23:45,220 --> 00:23:46,100
Rest up, Jim.

450
00:23:55,398 --> 00:23:57,539
- Stop. Stop, wait, wait, wait.
- All right.

451
00:23:57,540 --> 00:23:59,360
- Please.
- Okay, okay. All right.

452
00:23:59,730 --> 00:24:00,690
Okay.

453
00:24:01,180 --> 00:24:04,110
Are you willing to accept
the grace of repentance?

454
00:24:04,890 --> 00:24:05,890
I was wrong.

455
00:24:07,650 --> 00:24:09,840
The rain is... is-is a test.

456
00:24:10,910 --> 00:24:12,480
A test of my worthiness.

457
00:24:12,900 --> 00:24:13,950
Whose test?

458
00:24:15,930 --> 00:24:16,930
The dome.

459
00:24:18,310 --> 00:24:19,410
I believe that now.

460
00:24:22,760 --> 00:24:24,340
You're prepared to surrender?

461
00:24:25,700 --> 00:24:26,579
Yes. Yes.

462
00:24:26,580 --> 00:24:28,190
I-I believe in its plan.

463
00:24:28,970 --> 00:24:29,910
I do.

464
00:24:37,950 --> 00:24:39,860
No, you only believe in what you can see.

465
00:24:40,840 --> 00:24:41,840
Science.

466
00:24:45,160 --> 00:24:46,540
You're a lost cause.

467
00:24:53,330 --> 00:24:54,150
And now...

468
00:24:54,890 --> 00:24:56,209
No! No, no, no, no.

469
00:24:56,210 --> 00:24:57,770
- No, no...
- You're wasting my time.

470
00:25:00,080 --> 00:25:01,289
Drop it! Drop it!

471
00:25:01,290 --> 00:25:03,449
Put it on the ground!
Put it on the ground!

472
00:25:03,450 --> 00:25:04,630
Put your guns down!

473
00:25:05,970 --> 00:25:07,979
Put those guns on the ground!

474
00:25:07,980 --> 00:25:08,749
Put it down.

475
00:25:08,750 --> 00:25:10,070
On the ground!

476
00:25:10,560 --> 00:25:13,770
Put the guns on the ground now.

477
00:25:14,480 --> 00:25:15,400
There you go.

478
00:25:16,790 --> 00:25:18,670
I'll shoot her right in front of you.

479
00:25:20,600 --> 00:25:21,610
Now put that down.

480
00:25:28,500 --> 00:25:29,270
That's right.

481
00:25:32,130 --> 00:25:33,050
Damn!

482
00:25:33,170 --> 00:25:34,540
What is wrong with you?

483
00:25:37,360 --> 00:25:38,270
Lyle...

484
00:25:40,980 --> 00:25:42,050
Please don't hurt her.

485
00:25:44,950 --> 00:25:46,070
You know this rain is here

486
00:25:46,080 --> 00:25:48,170
to rid this town of nonbelievers.

487
00:25:49,270 --> 00:25:50,450
Now, you know that.

488
00:25:51,090 --> 00:25:53,270
I heard you talking to
those kids at the diner.

489
00:25:54,300 --> 00:25:55,350
You believe.

490
00:25:55,360 --> 00:25:56,460
Don't you, lady?

491
00:25:56,780 --> 00:25:57,720
I do.

492
00:25:58,240 --> 00:26:00,420
But I believe the dome
is here to protect us.

493
00:26:01,020 --> 00:26:02,300
Only the faithful.

494
00:26:02,760 --> 00:26:03,580
No.

495
00:26:04,150 --> 00:26:05,090
All of us.

496
00:26:09,260 --> 00:26:10,230
How do you know that?

497
00:26:11,330 --> 00:26:13,130
I know because the dome spoke to me.

498
00:26:14,770 --> 00:26:16,240
Maybe like it's spoken to you.

499
00:26:18,960 --> 00:26:19,820
Does the dome...

500
00:26:20,920 --> 00:26:22,630
Speak to you, Lyle?

501
00:26:24,440 --> 00:26:25,340
Nah.

502
00:26:26,220 --> 00:26:27,580
It doesn't speak to me.

503
00:26:28,620 --> 00:26:29,750
It's a feeling,

504
00:26:30,650 --> 00:26:32,350
directing my actions.

505
00:26:33,510 --> 00:26:34,740
Yeah, I understand.

506
00:26:36,910 --> 00:26:37,900
What'd it say to you?

507
00:26:39,500 --> 00:26:41,900
It says, "if you want
the darkness to abate,

508
00:26:42,890 --> 00:26:44,760
you must earn the light."

509
00:26:45,330 --> 00:26:46,380
Earn the light?

510
00:26:46,590 --> 00:26:49,580
Help me achieve the dome's true plan.

511
00:26:50,550 --> 00:26:51,450
Wh...

512
00:26:52,130 --> 00:26:53,110
What is that?

513
00:26:53,330 --> 00:26:54,640
I mean, its true plan?

514
00:26:55,190 --> 00:26:56,100
I don't know.

515
00:26:57,360 --> 00:26:58,790
But I have faith

516
00:26:59,030 --> 00:27:01,340
that the answers will be revealed.

517
00:27:04,860 --> 00:27:06,560
So give me the gun now, Lyle.

518
00:27:17,730 --> 00:27:19,050
Oh, God!

519
00:27:19,490 --> 00:27:20,389
Why would you do that?

520
00:27:20,390 --> 00:27:21,720
He was about to give in!

521
00:27:28,240 --> 00:27:28,959
Just get down.

522
00:27:28,960 --> 00:27:29,800
Stop!

523
00:27:32,520 --> 00:27:33,870
Signal's getting stronger.

524
00:27:34,030 --> 00:27:34,890
Joe?

525
00:27:46,690 --> 00:27:48,240
The source is coming from down there.

526
00:27:48,720 --> 00:27:50,230
You don't have to go.

527
00:28:00,420 --> 00:28:01,700
It's coming from here.

528
00:28:02,570 --> 00:28:03,140
Joe.

529
00:28:04,050 --> 00:28:05,350
Don't be frightened.

530
00:28:05,750 --> 00:28:07,680
How about you don't tell him how to be?

531
00:28:08,270 --> 00:28:09,309
You're not his girlfriend,

532
00:28:09,310 --> 00:28:11,370
and as far as I know, you're not anyone.

533
00:28:15,210 --> 00:28:16,120
Let's just go.

534
00:28:23,700 --> 00:28:26,210
That locker was the
last thing she touched.

535
00:28:27,720 --> 00:28:28,929
She died right here.

536
00:28:28,930 --> 00:28:30,930
Well, maybe we should just leave it alone.

537
00:28:31,610 --> 00:28:33,400
I have a bad feeling about this.

538
00:29:24,590 --> 00:29:25,400
It's empty.

539
00:29:26,940 --> 00:29:28,150
Now the signal's gone.

540
00:29:30,750 --> 00:29:32,610
How did you know that combination?

541
00:29:36,290 --> 00:29:38,150
Who the hell are you?

542
00:29:55,940 --> 00:29:56,700
All right.

543
00:30:25,950 --> 00:30:27,900
Oh, it's-it's okay. Easy now.

544
00:30:30,220 --> 00:30:31,220
Are you okay?

545
00:30:31,640 --> 00:30:32,410
I'm fine.

546
00:30:36,410 --> 00:30:37,220
Lyle?

547
00:30:37,510 --> 00:30:38,380
He's in jail.

548
00:30:39,040 --> 00:30:41,510
Trust me, he looks a lot worse than we do.

549
00:30:43,900 --> 00:30:45,050
Rain stopped.

550
00:30:46,320 --> 00:30:47,510
I stopped it.

551
00:30:48,580 --> 00:30:50,810
Not the dome. Me.

552
00:30:51,660 --> 00:30:52,360
How?

553
00:30:52,900 --> 00:30:55,490
A mixture of salination
with some high ph compounds.

554
00:30:56,400 --> 00:30:58,079
It's pretty sciencey.

555
00:30:58,080 --> 00:31:00,080
I thought that stuff didn't interest you.

556
00:31:02,720 --> 00:31:04,250
- It interests me.
- Good.

557
00:31:04,700 --> 00:31:07,430
Because I took a tour of the
town after the rain stopped.

558
00:31:10,110 --> 00:31:11,970
Our situation has only gotten worse.

559
00:31:13,330 --> 00:31:15,120
Some tough decisions need to be made.

560
00:31:17,430 --> 00:31:18,880
What kind of decisions?

561
00:31:21,430 --> 00:31:23,579
Listen, bitch, I am so over

562
00:31:23,580 --> 00:31:25,739
this little miss innocent
scam you're running,

563
00:31:25,740 --> 00:31:28,299
and we are not leaving
until you come clean

564
00:31:28,300 --> 00:31:30,369
about how you knew that combination

565
00:31:30,370 --> 00:31:32,650
- and why the signal got blocked.
- I don't know.

566
00:31:33,110 --> 00:31:34,719
What, are you a safecracker?

567
00:31:34,720 --> 00:31:35,759
A magician's assistant?

568
00:31:35,760 --> 00:31:38,689
Because, when we got here,
the locker was locked,

569
00:31:38,690 --> 00:31:41,230
and then presto, change-o,
you opened it right up.

570
00:31:41,260 --> 00:31:42,510
Norrie, she doesn't know.

571
00:31:42,880 --> 00:31:46,129
It was just like I saw it in my head.

572
00:31:46,130 --> 00:31:48,150
In your head. Oh, in here?

573
00:31:49,010 --> 00:31:51,289
What else is in there?
Is your name in there?

574
00:31:51,290 --> 00:31:52,970
- Norrie, stop!
- No!

575
00:31:52,980 --> 00:31:54,909
She just shows up here
without any explanation

576
00:31:54,910 --> 00:31:57,799
on the day your sister gets
killed in front of that locker,

577
00:31:57,800 --> 00:32:00,080
and just happens to know the combination?

578
00:32:00,420 --> 00:32:01,730
How did you know?

579
00:32:02,400 --> 00:32:03,179
How did you know?!

580
00:32:03,180 --> 00:32:04,670
Leave me alone!

581
00:32:04,920 --> 00:32:06,890
I'm telling the truth!

582
00:32:07,420 --> 00:32:08,769
Why don't you trust her?

583
00:32:08,770 --> 00:32:10,269
She just saw it?

584
00:32:10,270 --> 00:32:11,439
That doesn't even make sense.

585
00:32:11,440 --> 00:32:13,679
How do you see a combination?

586
00:32:13,680 --> 00:32:16,760
Actually, I think I might know.

587
00:32:19,610 --> 00:32:21,070
As I've been telling Jim,

588
00:32:21,300 --> 00:32:24,149
we have a serious resource
crisis to deal with.

589
00:32:24,150 --> 00:32:26,869
I thought that that's what
this whole registration drive

590
00:32:26,870 --> 00:32:27,899
was about in the first place,

591
00:32:27,900 --> 00:32:29,749
this is about how to better allocate them.

592
00:32:29,750 --> 00:32:33,119
Yes, but it's a lack
of resources themselves

593
00:32:33,120 --> 00:32:34,649
that I'm most worried about.

594
00:32:34,650 --> 00:32:37,129
Even before today, there
were acute shortages.

595
00:32:37,130 --> 00:32:38,699
And after the rain?

596
00:32:38,700 --> 00:32:42,309
Far fewer medical
supplies, crops destroyed.

597
00:32:42,310 --> 00:32:44,259
A considerable amount
of livestock decimated,

598
00:32:44,260 --> 00:32:46,100
especially in the pig population.

599
00:32:48,700 --> 00:32:51,880
Day's coming when there won't
be enough food to sustain us.

600
00:32:56,220 --> 00:32:56,950
So,

601
00:32:57,850 --> 00:32:59,529
we should have a contingency plan

602
00:32:59,530 --> 00:33:01,330
in case we run out of options.

603
00:33:02,350 --> 00:33:04,150
What kind of contingency plan?

604
00:33:05,430 --> 00:33:06,840
It may become necessary...

605
00:33:08,270 --> 00:33:10,050
Selectively, I'm saying...

606
00:33:11,020 --> 00:33:12,100
To thin the herd.

607
00:33:13,220 --> 00:33:14,560
Selectively?

608
00:33:27,600 --> 00:33:29,120
The questions on your form...

609
00:33:29,600 --> 00:33:32,350
Family background,
history of illness...

610
00:33:33,170 --> 00:33:38,469
This is a census, to help you
decide who lives and who dies.

611
00:33:38,470 --> 00:33:39,470
Let's get out of here.

612
00:33:49,150 --> 00:33:51,580
She's just talking about a contingency.

613
00:34:02,530 --> 00:34:04,000
Trouble in paradise.

614
00:34:04,260 --> 00:34:07,219
Julia? Listen, you don't understand.

615
00:34:07,220 --> 00:34:09,519
I understand. You're taking their side!

616
00:34:09,520 --> 00:34:11,629
No, no, no, I am not
taking anyone's side here.

617
00:34:11,630 --> 00:34:13,339
I'm trying to consider
every possible option.

618
00:34:13,340 --> 00:34:14,789
You said, when things fall apart,

619
00:34:14,790 --> 00:34:16,519
people show their true colors.

620
00:34:16,520 --> 00:34:17,440
Are these yours?

621
00:34:18,320 --> 00:34:19,080
I need to know that

622
00:34:19,090 --> 00:34:22,449
you will stand with me
against them, against that!

623
00:34:22,450 --> 00:34:24,489
They don't get to throw
anybody out of the lifeboat!

624
00:34:24,490 --> 00:34:25,599
What if it's sinking?

625
00:34:25,600 --> 00:34:27,390
I believe we will find a way.

626
00:34:28,490 --> 00:34:30,410
Belief only gets you so far.

627
00:34:31,510 --> 00:34:34,010
I thought I knew you. I was wrong.

628
00:34:35,820 --> 00:34:37,310
Don't follow me!

629
00:34:42,260 --> 00:34:45,090
*long as I remember*

630
00:34:45,900 --> 00:34:50,490
*rain's been coming down*

631
00:34:51,870 --> 00:34:54,899
*clouds of mystery pouring*

632
00:34:54,900 --> 00:34:59,340
*confusion on the ground*

633
00:35:00,840 --> 00:35:03,940
*good men through the ages*

634
00:35:04,340 --> 00:35:07,400
*trying to find the sun*

635
00:35:09,450 --> 00:35:12,429
*and I wonder, still I wonder*

636
00:35:12,430 --> 00:35:15,940
*who'll stop the rain*

637
00:35:23,470 --> 00:35:24,940
I was wondering when you'd show up.

638
00:35:25,660 --> 00:35:27,840
Aren't you afraid of
people seeing us together?

639
00:35:30,440 --> 00:35:31,500
Building's empty.

640
00:35:33,480 --> 00:35:35,750
I could kill you, and nobody'd know.

641
00:35:37,810 --> 00:35:38,960
Nobody'd care.

642
00:35:39,740 --> 00:35:40,530
Maybe.

643
00:35:41,960 --> 00:35:42,880
But you won't.

644
00:35:44,900 --> 00:35:46,180
When this thing came down,

645
00:35:47,480 --> 00:35:51,160
I told you to lay low, follow my lead.

646
00:35:52,020 --> 00:35:53,199
I got a new leader.

647
00:35:53,200 --> 00:35:55,609
You made a promise 25 years ago

648
00:35:55,610 --> 00:35:58,930
to make sure that what
we buried stayed buried.

649
00:35:59,830 --> 00:36:01,650
You've heard of force majeure, yeah?

650
00:36:04,550 --> 00:36:06,229
An extraordinary circumstance

651
00:36:06,230 --> 00:36:08,910
that frees both parties from a contract.

652
00:36:09,310 --> 00:36:10,250
Well, you know what?

653
00:36:11,100 --> 00:36:15,060
This dome is about as
majeure a force as it gets.

654
00:36:17,770 --> 00:36:19,840
But it's gonna deliver
us to a better place.

655
00:36:20,410 --> 00:36:22,580
I'm afraid you got that
exactly backward, pal.

656
00:36:27,450 --> 00:36:30,010
I grow weary of this conversation.

657
00:36:30,820 --> 00:36:32,670
See you on the other side, Sammy.

658
00:36:44,870 --> 00:36:47,090
I read about a tribe in Borneo.

659
00:36:47,100 --> 00:36:48,399
I can't remember what they were called.

660
00:36:48,400 --> 00:36:51,179
But they had this ritual,

661
00:36:51,180 --> 00:36:53,399
something that they would do every year.

662
00:36:53,400 --> 00:36:55,539
They'd put all their elderly,

663
00:36:55,540 --> 00:36:57,169
their infirm, up into a tree,

664
00:36:57,170 --> 00:36:58,830
and they would shake it.

665
00:36:58,840 --> 00:37:00,759
And whoever held on

666
00:37:00,760 --> 00:37:02,869
was considered strong enough,

667
00:37:02,870 --> 00:37:05,240
useful enough to make it to the next year.

668
00:37:07,250 --> 00:37:08,660
Those that couldn't hold on?

669
00:37:10,180 --> 00:37:11,180
Look, um...

670
00:37:13,350 --> 00:37:15,699
When I said the day was coming

671
00:37:15,700 --> 00:37:18,199
we wouldn't have provisions
enough to sustain the population,

672
00:37:18,200 --> 00:37:19,510
that was a bit of a cheat.

673
00:37:22,530 --> 00:37:23,759
That day isn't coming.

674
00:37:23,760 --> 00:37:24,640
It's now.

675
00:37:25,910 --> 00:37:28,299
The way I calculate it, we can all starve

676
00:37:28,300 --> 00:37:30,859
or with proper rationing and cultivation,

677
00:37:30,860 --> 00:37:32,740
three-quarters of us can survive.

678
00:37:34,190 --> 00:37:35,970
And how do you propose to do that?

679
00:37:37,580 --> 00:37:38,650
Shake the tree?

680
00:37:40,300 --> 00:37:42,319
You could use the
information we gathered today

681
00:37:42,320 --> 00:37:44,710
to determine who's an
asset and who's a burden.

682
00:37:45,890 --> 00:37:48,340
Those hard choices could
be made but not by me.

683
00:37:49,540 --> 00:37:51,100
Dome chose you to make them.

684
00:37:53,110 --> 00:37:54,400
And you've got to do it now.

685
00:37:55,110 --> 00:37:56,380
Before it's too late.

686
00:38:03,760 --> 00:38:04,460
Man!

687
00:38:06,250 --> 00:38:07,400
We need to talk.

688
00:38:08,780 --> 00:38:10,100
I guess you found out.

689
00:38:10,490 --> 00:38:11,920
That my mother's alive?

690
00:38:13,920 --> 00:38:15,700
She told me you'd have answers.

691
00:38:16,390 --> 00:38:18,450
To some pretty provocative questions.

692
00:38:18,900 --> 00:38:20,410
Do you know who killed Angie?

693
00:38:24,700 --> 00:38:25,450
I might.

694
00:38:25,750 --> 00:38:27,730
Is that what you and my
Uncle were talking about?

695
00:38:29,790 --> 00:38:31,590
I need you to tell me everything!

696
00:38:33,760 --> 00:38:35,390
Uh, I can do that.

697
00:38:37,580 --> 00:38:40,170
Provided you give
consideration to my needs.

698
00:38:43,140 --> 00:38:43,970
Which are?

699
00:38:44,530 --> 00:38:45,820
You let me out of here.

700
00:38:47,860 --> 00:38:49,660
I'll give you an all-access pass.

701
00:38:54,090 --> 00:38:56,160
What do you say, James?

702
00:38:57,850 --> 00:38:59,439
What was the locker number again?

703
00:39:01,720 --> 00:39:02,529
Here we go.

704
00:39:02,530 --> 00:39:05,819
People who have had that
locker over the last 50 years.

705
00:39:05,820 --> 00:39:07,769
Okay, what exactly are we looking for?

706
00:39:07,770 --> 00:39:09,330
Anything to jog her memory.

707
00:39:13,880 --> 00:39:14,610
Wait.

708
00:39:15,880 --> 00:39:17,369
Melanie cross?

709
00:39:17,370 --> 00:39:18,710
That looks familiar to you?

710
00:39:19,710 --> 00:39:21,099
Something about it.

711
00:39:21,100 --> 00:39:22,380
1988.

712
00:39:24,080 --> 00:39:25,900
I'll pull the yearbook for that year.

713
00:39:29,910 --> 00:39:30,600
Okay.

714
00:39:33,550 --> 00:39:34,560
Brazier,

715
00:39:35,310 --> 00:39:36,220
Connor,

716
00:39:36,900 --> 00:39:37,760
cross.

717
00:39:40,420 --> 00:39:41,900
How is this possible?

718
00:39:42,940 --> 00:39:43,700
What?

719
00:39:44,610 --> 00:39:45,490
What is it?

720
00:39:52,060 --> 00:39:55,330
It's... me.

721
00:39:55,639 --> 00:40:11,019
